surface: Approx. half dull green, half dark brown, dry surface much pock-scarred - a few with pale green corrosion deposits within. Whole surface appears lost leaving v. rounded featues.
description: Typology: body angles rounded - poss. due to condition [;] Manufacture: limits of possible edge bevel about 5.5 mm in from edge; plano-convex profile poss. from casting in open mould unless subsequent damage; irregular fissure extends across about half of body from one side - poss. casting flaw or damage? [;] Condition: present "squared off" blade tips come to rounded edges not dissimilar from rest of edge - therefore not certain whether blade tips broken off ; indentation in side of butt associated with filing biting gold metal - prob. would have been symmetrical.
remarks: Discovered using a metal detector on farmland at the position marked on map in DF just to the west of the River Misbourne, by Mr. Miller of Feltham; probably a very recent find; permission of the farmer apparently obtained.
publications: None

remarks: Mr. K.R. Sansbury wrote, 4 Nov. 1927 that in his opinion the 2 parts do not belong to the same implement. They do not fit. The edge portion has been hooked or broken, the butt end does not show similar treatment and is at least 0.5 wider at the fracture, it has also a flaw not perceptible in the edge portion. The patinations differ, the edge being greenish, the butt purple-brown & the composition does not appear to be the same. The butt is a roughly cast implement, the edge well finished
publications: Trans. Carmarthen Antiq. Soc. Vol XIII p. xi [;] Sansbury, Cards. Antiq. Soc., VII 83-4, Figs. p.79

description: Traces of incised decoration in middle of face. This tapers from centre. Is sharp edge & butt. The widest part of side is plain, but between middle and edge there is a suggestion of facets on the sides. Ripples are not so cleanly defined on reverse. The 2 raised lines (running across ripples) are from the mould. There is another, much shorter, slanting in from the edge.
collection: In a private collection April 1924 [;] Mr. Hemp obtained [;] The information obtained by Mr. Wilfred J. Hemp [;] Now N.M.W. Cardiff, Dec 1976
remarks: It has been said that these ripples form a decoration, but they may have been caused by the molten metal being poured into a cold mould.
publications: Hemp, Arch. Camb., 1924, 329-331, Figs. 2,3 ; [;] Megan & Hartley, Pr. Prehist. Soc., 1938, no. 23
